APPEND.summary: Append a value to a key
APPEND.complexity: O(1). The amortized time complexity is O(1) assuming the appended value is small and the already present value is of any size, since the dynamic string library used by Redis will double the free space available on every reallocation.

BGSAVE.summary: Asynchronously save the dataset to disk

BITCOUNT.summary: Count set bits in a string

BITPOS.summary: Find first bit set or clear in a string

BLPOP.summary: Remove and get the first element in a list, or block until one is available

BRPOP.summary: Remove and get the last element in a list, or block until one is available

BRPOPLPUSH.summary: Pop a value from a list, push it to another list and return it; or block until one is available

CLIENT KILL.summary: Kill the connection of a client
CLIENT KILL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of client connections

CLIENT LIST.summary: Get the list of client connections
CLIENT LIST.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of client connections

CLIENT PAUSE.summary: Stop processing commands from clients for some time

CLIENT REPLY.summary: Instruct the server whether to reply to commands

CLUSTER ADDSLOTS.summary: Assign new hash slots to receiving node
CLUSTER ADDSLOTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of hash slot arguments

CLUSTER COUNT-FAILURE-REPORTS.summary: Return the number of failure reports active for a given node
CLUSTER COUNT-FAILURE-REPORTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of failure reports

CLUSTER COUNTKEYSINSLOT.summary: Return the number of local keys in the specified hash slot

CLUSTER DELSLOTS.summary: Set hash slots as unbound in receiving node
CLUSTER DELSLOTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of hash slot arguments

CLUSTER FAILOVER.summary: Forces a slave to perform a manual failover of its master.

CLUSTER FORGET.summary: Remove a node from the nodes table

CLUSTER GETKEYSINSLOT.summary: Return local key names in the specified hash slot
CLUSTER GETKEYSINSLOT.complexity: O(log(N)) where N is the number of requested keys

CLUSTER INFO.summary: Provides info about Redis Cluster node state

CLUSTER KEYSLOT.summary: Returns the hash slot of the specified key
CLUSTER KEYSLOT.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of bytes in the key

CLUSTER MEET.summary: Force a node cluster to handshake with another node

CLUSTER NODES.summary: Get Cluster config for the node
CLUSTER NODES.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

CLUSTER REPLICATE.summary: Reconfigure a node as a slave of the specified master node

CLUSTER RESET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of known nodes. The command may execute a FLUSHALL as a side effect.

CLUSTER SAVECONFIG.summary: Forces the node to save cluster state on disk

CLUSTER SET-CONFIG-EPOCH.summary: Set the configuration epoch in a new node

CLUSTER SETSLOT.summary: Bind a hash slot to a specific node

CLUSTER SLAVES.summary: List slave nodes of the specified master node

CLUSTER SLOTS.summary: Get array of Cluster slot to node mappings
CLUSTER SLOTS.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

COMMAND.summary: Get array of Redis command details
COMMAND.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Redis commands

COMMAND COUNT.summary: Get total number of Redis commands

COMMAND GETKEYS.summary: Extract keys given a full Redis command
COMMAND GETKEYS.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of arguments to the command

COMMAND INFO.summary: Get array of specific Redis command details
COMMAND INFO.complexity: O(N) when N is number of commands to look up

CONFIG GET.summary: Get the value of a configuration parameter

CONFIG REWRITE.summary: Rewrite the configuration file with the in memory configuration

CONFIG SET.summary: Set a configuration parameter to the given value

CONFIG RESETSTAT.summary: Reset the stats returned by INFO

DBSIZE.summary: Return the number of keys in the selected database

DEBUG OBJECT.summary: Get debugging information about a key

DECR.summary: Decrement the integer value of a key by one

DECRBY.summary: Decrement the integer value of a key by the given number

DEL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys that will be removed. When a key to remove holds a value other than a string, the individual complexity for this key is O(M) where M is the number of elements in the list, set, sorted set or hash. Removing a single key that holds a string value is O(1).

DISCARD.summary: Discard all commands issued after MULTI

DUMP.summary: Return a serialized version of the value stored at the specified key.
DUMP.complexity: O(1) to access the key and additional O(N*M) to serialized it, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1).

EVAL.summary: Execute a Lua script server side
EVAL.complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

EVALSHA.summary: Execute a Lua script server side
EVALSHA.complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

EXEC.summary: Execute all commands issued after MULTI

EXPIRE.summary: Set a key's time to live in seconds

EXPIREAT.summary: Set the expiration for a key as a UNIX timestamp

FLUSHALL.summary: Remove all keys from all databases

FLUSHDB.summary: Remove all keys from the current database

GEOADD.summary: Add one or more geospatial items in the geospatial index represented using a sorted set
GEOADD.complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

GEOHASH.summary: Returns members of a geospatial index as standard geohash strings
GEOHASH.complexity: O(log(N)) for each member requested, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

GEOPOS.summary: Returns longitude and latitude of members of a geospatial index
GEOPOS.complexity: O(log(N)) for each member requested, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

GEODIST.summary: Returns the distance between two members of a geospatial index

GEORADIUS.summary: Query a sorted set representing a geospatial index to fetch members matching a given maximum distance from a point
GEORADIUS.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

GEORADIUSBYMEMBER.summary: Query a sorted set representing a geospatial index to fetch members matching a given maximum distance from a member
GEORADIUSBYMEMBER.complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

GET.summary: Get the value of a key

GETBIT.summary: Returns the bit value at offset in the string value stored at key

GETRANGE.summary: Get a substring of the string stored at a key
GETRANGE.complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the returned string. The complexity is ultimately determined by the returned length, but because creating a substring from an existing string is very cheap, it can be considered O(1) for small strings.

GETSET.summary: Set the string value of a key and return its old value

HDEL.summary: Delete one or more hash fields
HDEL.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields to be removed.

HEXISTS.summary: Determine if a hash field exists

HGET.summary: Get the value of a hash field

HGETALL.summary: Get all the fields and values in a hash
HGETALL.complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

HINCRBY.summary: Increment the integer value of a hash field by the given number

HINCRBYFLOAT.summary: Increment the float value of a hash field by the given amount

HKEYS.summary: Get all the fields in a hash
HKEYS.complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

HLEN.summary: Get the number of fields in a hash

HMGET.summary: Get the values of all the given hash fields
HMGET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields being requested.

HMSET.summary: Set multiple hash fields to multiple values
HMSET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields being set.

HSET.summary: Set the string value of a hash field

HSETNX.summary: Set the value of a hash field, only if the field does not exist

HSTRLEN.summary: Get the length of the value of a hash field

HVALS.summary: Get all the values in a hash
HVALS.complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

INCR.summary: Increment the integer value of a key by one

INCRBY.summary: Increment the integer value of a key by the given amount

INCRBYFLOAT.summary: Increment the float value of a key by the given amount

INFO.summary: Get information and statistics about the server

KEYS.summary: Find all keys matching the given pattern
KEYS.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of keys in the database, under the assumption that the key names in the database and the given pattern have limited length.

LASTSAVE.summary: Get the UNIX time stamp of the last successful save to disk

LINDEX.summary: Get an element from a list by its index
LINDEX.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to traverse to get to the element at index. This makes asking for the first or the last element of the list O(1).

LINSERT.summary: Insert an element before or after another element in a list
LINSERT.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to traverse before seeing the value pivot. This means that inserting somewhere on the left end on the list (head) can be considered O(1) and inserting somewhere on the right end (tail) is O(N).

LLEN.summary: Get the length of a list

LPOP.summary: Remove and get the first element in a list

LPUSH.summary: Prepend one or multiple values to a list

LPUSHX.summary: Prepend a value to a list, only if the list exists

LRANGE.summary: Get a range of elements from a list
LRANGE.complexity: O(S+N) where S is the distance of start offset from HEAD for small lists, from nearest end (HEAD or TAIL) for large lists; and N is the number of elements in the specified range.

LREM.complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the list.

LSET.summary: Set the value of an element in a list by its index
LSET.complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the list. Setting either the first or the last element of the list is O(1).

LTRIM.summary: Trim a list to the specified range
LTRIM.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to be removed by the operation.

MGET.summary: Get the values of all the given keys
MGET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to retrieve.

MIGRATE.summary: Atomically transfer a key from a Redis instance to another one.
MIGRATE.complexity: This command actually executes a DUMP+DEL in the source instance, and a RESTORE in the target instance. See the pages of these commands for time complexity. Also an O(N) data transfer between the two instances is performed.

MONITOR.summary: Listen for all requests received by the server in real time

MOVE.summary: Move a key to another database

MSET.summary: Set multiple keys to multiple values
MSET.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to set.

MSETNX.summary: Set multiple keys to multiple values, only if none of the keys exist
MSETNX.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to set.

MULTI.summary: Mark the start of a transaction block

OBJECT.summary: Inspect the internals of Redis objects
OBJECT.complexity: O(1) for all the currently implemented subcommands.

PERSIST.summary: Remove the expiration from a key

PEXPIRE.summary: Set a key's time to live in milliseconds

PEXPIREAT.summary: Set the expiration for a key as a UNIX timestamp specified in milliseconds

PFADD.summary: Adds all the elements arguments to the HyperLogLog data structure stored at the variable name specified as first argument.

PFCOUNT.summary: Return the approximated cardinality of the set(s) observed by the HyperLogLog at key(s).
PFCOUNT.complexity: O(1) with every small average constant times when called with a single key. O(N) with N being the number of keys, and much bigger constant times, when called with multiple keys.

PFMERGE.summary: Merge N different HyperLogLogs into a single one.
PFMERGE.complexity: O(N) to merge N HyperLogLogs, but with high constant times.

PSETEX.summary: Set the value and expiration in milliseconds of a key

PSUBSCRIBE.summary: Listen for messages published to channels matching the given patterns
PSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of patterns the client is already subscribed to.

PUBSUB.summary: Inspect the state of the Pub/Sub subsystem
PUBSUB.complexity: O(N) for the CHANNELS subcommand, where N is the number of active channels, and assuming constant time pattern matching (relatively short channels and patterns). O(N) for the NUMSUB subcommand, where N is the number of requested channels. O(1) for the NUMPAT subcommand.

PTTL.summary: Get the time to live for a key in milliseconds

PUBLISH.summary: Post a message to a channel
PUBLISH.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of clients subscribed to the receiving channel and M is the total number of subscribed patterns (by any client).

PUNSUBSCRIBE.summary: Stop listening for messages posted to channels matching the given patterns
PUNSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of patterns the client is already subscribed and M is the number of total patterns subscribed in the system (by any client).

RANDOMKEY.summary: Return a random key from the keyspace

READONLY.summary: Enables read queries for a connection to a cluster slave node

READWRITE.summary: Disables read queries for a connection to a cluster slave node

RENAMENX.summary: Rename a key, only if the new key does not exist

RESTORE.summary: Create a key using the provided serialized value, previously obtained using DUMP.
RESTORE.complexity: O(1) to create the new key and additional O(N*M) to reconstruct the serialized value, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1). However for sorted set values the complexity is O(N*M*log(N)) because inserting values into sorted sets is O(log(N)).

ROLE.summary: Return the role of the instance in the context of replication

RPOP.summary: Remove and get the last element in a list

RPOPLPUSH.summary: Remove the last element in a list, prepend it to another list and return it

RPUSH.summary: Append one or multiple values to a list

RPUSHX.summary: Append a value to a list, only if the list exists

SADD.summary: Add one or more members to a set
SADD.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members to be added.

SAVE.summary: Synchronously save the dataset to disk

SCARD.summary: Get the number of members in a set

SCRIPT DEBUG.summary: Set the debug mode for executed scripts.

SCRIPT EXISTS.summary: Check existence of scripts in the script cache.
SCRIPT EXISTS.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of scripts to check (so checking a single script is an O(1) operation).

SCRIPT FLUSH.summary: Remove all the scripts from the script cache.
SCRIPT FLUSH.complexity: O(N) with N being the number of scripts in cache

SCRIPT KILL.summary: Kill the script currently in execution.

SCRIPT LOAD.summary: Load the specified Lua script into the script cache.
SCRIPT LOAD.complexity: O(N) with N being the length in bytes of the script body.

SDIFF.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SDIFFSTORE.summary: Subtract multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key
SDIFFSTORE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SELECT.summary: Change the selected database for the current connection

SET.summary: Set the string value of a key

SETBIT.summary: Sets or clears the bit at offset in the string value stored at key

SETEX.summary: Set the value and expiration of a key

SETNX.summary: Set the value of a key, only if the key does not exist

SETRANGE.summary: Overwrite part of a string at key starting at the specified offset
SETRANGE.complexity: O(1), not counting the time taken to copy the new string in place. Usually, this string is very small so the amortized complexity is O(1). Otherwise, complexity is O(M) with M being the length of the value argument.

SHUTDOWN.summary: Synchronously save the dataset to disk and then shut down the server

SINTER.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

SINTERSTORE.summary: Intersect multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key
SINTERSTORE.complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

SISMEMBER.summary: Determine if a given value is a member of a set

SLAVEOF.summary: Make the server a slave of another instance, or promote it as master

SLOWLOG.summary: Manages the Redis slow queries log

SMEMBERS.summary: Get all the members in a set
SMEMBERS.complexity: O(N) where N is the set cardinality.

SMOVE.summary: Move a member from one set to another

SORT.summary: Sort the elements in a list, set or sorted set
SORT.complexity: O(N+M*log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the list or set to sort, and M the number of returned elements. When the elements are not sorted, complexity is currently O(N) as there is a copy step that will be avoided in next releases.

SPOP.summary: Remove and return one or multiple random members from a set

SRANDMEMBER.summary: Get one or multiple random members from a set
SRANDMEMBER.complexity: Without the count argument O(1), otherwise O(N) where N is the absolute value of the passed count.

SREM.summary: Remove one or more members from a set
SREM.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members to be removed.

STRLEN.summary: Get the length of the value stored in a key

SUBSCRIBE.summary: Listen for messages published to the given channels
SUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of channels to subscribe to.

SUNION.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

SUNIONSTORE.summary: Add multiple sets and store the resulting set in a key
SUNIONSTORE.complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

TTL.summary: Get the time to live for a key

TYPE.summary: Determine the type stored at key

UNSUBSCRIBE.summary: Stop listening for messages posted to the given channels
UNSUBSCRIBE.complexity: O(N) where N is the number of clients already subscribed to a channel.

WAIT.summary: Wait for the synchronous replication of all the write commands sent in the context of the current connection

WATCH.summary: Watch the given keys to determine execution of the MULTI/EXEC block

ZADD.summary: Add one or more members to a sorted set, or update its score if it already exists
ZADD.complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZCARD.summary: Get the number of members in a sorted set

ZCOUNT.summary: Count the members in a sorted set with scores within the given values
ZCOUNT.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZINCRBY.summary: Increment the score of a member in a sorted set
ZINCRBY.complexity: O(log(N)) where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZINTERSTORE.summary: Intersect multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key
ZINTERSTORE.complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

ZLEXCOUNT.summary: Count the number of members in a sorted set between a given lexicographical range
ZLEXCOUNT.complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

ZRANGE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by index
ZRANGE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.

ZRANGEBYLEX.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by lexicographical range
ZRANGEBYLEX.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZREVRANGEBYLEX.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by lexicographical range, ordered from higher to lower strings.
ZREVRANGEBYLEX.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZRANGEBYSCORE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by score
ZRANGEBYSCORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZRANK.summary: Determine the index of a member in a sorted set

ZREM.summary: Remove one or more members from a sorted set
ZREM.complexity: O(M*log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements to be removed.

ZREMRANGEBYLEX.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set between the given lexicographical range
ZREMRANGEBYLEX.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

ZREMRANGEBYRANK.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set within the given indexes
ZREMRANGEBYRANK.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

ZREMRANGEBYSCORE.summary: Remove all members in a sorted set within the given scores
ZREMRANGEBYSCORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

ZREVRANGE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by index, with scores ordered from high to low
ZREVRANGE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.

ZREVRANGEBYSCORE.summary: Return a range of members in a sorted set, by score, with scores ordered from high to low
ZREVRANGEBYSCORE.complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

ZREVRANK.summary: Determine the index of a member in a sorted set, with scores ordered from high to low

ZSCORE.summary: Get the score associated with the given member in a sorted set

ZUNIONSTORE.summary: Add multiple sorted sets and store the resulting sorted set in a new key
ZUNIONSTORE.complexity: O(N)+O(M log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

SCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

SSCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..

HSCAN.summary: Incrementally iterate hash fields and associated values
HSCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..

ZSCAN.summary: Incrementally iterate sorted sets elements and associated scores
ZSCAN.complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection..
